    <section class="learning-objectives" id="sect-00001">
      <title>Learning Objectives</title>
      <para id="para-00001">After completing this module, you should be able to:</para>
      <list list-type="enumerated" id="list-00001">
      <item>Apply the law of detachment to determine the conclusion of a pair of statements.</item>
      <item>Apply the law of denying the consequent to determine the conclusion for pairs of statements.</item>
      <item>Apply the chain rule to determine valid conclusions for pairs of true statements.</item>
      </list>
      </section>
      <para id="para-00002">The previous modules in this chapter provide the foundational skills for constructing and analyzing <term id="term-00001">logical arguments</term>. All logical arguments include a set of premises that support a claim or conclusion; but not all logical arguments are <term id="term-00002">valid</term> and <term id="term-00003">sound</term>. A false or deceptive argument is called a <term id="term-00004">fallacy.</term> Many types of fallacies are so common that they have been named.</para>
      <note class="definition" id="note-00001">
      <para id="para-00003">A <emphasis effect="bold">logical argument</emphasis> uses a series of facts or premises to justify a conclusion or claim.</para>
      <para id="para-00004">A logical argument is <emphasis effect="bold">valid</emphasis> if its conclusion follows from the premises.</para>
      <para id="para-00005">A logical argument is <emphasis effect="bold">sound</emphasis> if it is valid, and all of its premises are true.</para>
      <para id="para-00006">A <emphasis effect="bold">fallacy</emphasis> is a false or deceptive argument.</para>
      </note>
      <note class="who-knew" id="note-00002">
      <para id="para-00007">Dale Carnegie the author of the book “How to Win Friends and Influence People” developed and marketed training materials for improving public speaking and negotiation skills beginning in 1915 that are still used today. He famously said, “When dealing with people, remember you are not dealing with creatures of logic, but creatures of emotion.”</para>
      <para id="para-00008">Many fallacious logical arguments use our susceptibility to emotional appeals to try to convince us that what they are saying is true. The study of logic helps us combat this weakness through recognition and learning to focus on the facts and structure of the argument.</para>
      </note>
      <para id="para-00009">The focus of this module is the two main forms that logical arguments can take. <term id="term-00005">Deductive arguments</term> attempt to draw specific conclusions from a least one or more general <term id="term-00006">premises</term>, while <term id="term-00007">inductive arguments</term> attempt to draw a more general conclusion from a pattern of specific premises.</para>
      <note class="definition" id="note-00003">
      <para id="para-00010"><emphasis effect="bold">Deductive arguments</emphasis> draw specific conclusions from more general premises. A deductive argument can be shown to be valid using a truth table or Venn diagram.</para>
      <para id="para-00011">A<emphasis effect="bold"> premise</emphasis> is a logical statement used as a fact to support the claim made by a logical argument.</para>
      <para id="para-00012">An <emphasis effect="bold">inductive argument</emphasis> uses a series of specific premises to draw a more general conclusion.</para>
      </note>
      <para id="para-00013">Inductive arguments generally cannot be proven to be true, they are judged as being strong or weak, but, like any opinion, whether you believe an argument is strong or weak often depends on your knowledge of the topic being discussed along with the evidence being provided in the premises.  Hasty generalization is the name given to any fallacy that presents a weak inductive argument.</para>
      <para id="para-00014">Deductive arguments can be proven to be valid using Venn diagrams or truth tables.</para>
      <note class="check-point" id="note-00013">
      <para id="para-00015"><emphasis effect="italic">Be Careful! Premises may be true or false.  If a premise is false, the claims made by the argument should be questioned.</emphasis></para>
      </note>
      <section id="sect-00002">
      <title> Law of Detachment</title>
      <para id="para-00016">The <term id="term-00008">law of detachment</term> is a form of a conditional argument that asserts both the conditional, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow></math> is true and the hypothesis, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mi>p</mi></math> is also true, then makes the claim that <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mi>q</mi></math> true. The law of detachment is also called affirming the hypothesis (or antecedent) and modus ponens. Arguments that have this form are valid.</para>
      <note class="definition" id="note-00004" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">
      <para id="para-00017">The <emphasis effect="bold">law of detachment</emphasis> is a valid form of a conditional argument that asserts that if both the conditional, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow></math> is true and the hypothesis, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mi>p</mi></math> is true, then the conclusion <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mi>q</mi></math> must also be true. Symbolically it has the form: <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>∧</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>→</mo><mi>q</mi><mo>.</mo></mrow></math></para>
      </note>
