      </note>
      <note class="check-point" id="note-00016" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">
      <para id="para-00029" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><emphasis effect="italic">The conditional statement can also be described as, “If antecedent, then consequent.”  This is where the law of denying the consequent gets its name.</emphasis></para>
      </note>
      <para id="para-00030">To verify if the law of denying the consequent is a valid argument, construct a truth table for the argument, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>∧</mo><mo>~</mo><mi>q</mi></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>→</mo><mtext> </mtext><mo>~</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow></math> and verify that it is a tautology.</para>
      <table summary="." id="table-00005" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">
      <title><emphasis effect="italic">Truth Table Demonstrating the Law of Denying the Consequent Is a Tautology</emphasis></title>
      <tgroup cols="7">
      <colspec colnum="1" colname="c1" colwidth="1*"/>
      <colspec colnum="2" colname="c2" colwidth="1*"/>
      <colspec colnum="3" colname="c3" colwidth="1*"/>
      <colspec colnum="4" colname="c4" colwidth="1*"/>
      <colspec colnum="5" colname="c5" colwidth="1*"/>
      <colspec colnum="6" colname="c6" colwidth="1*"/>
      <colspec colnum="7" colname="c7" colwidth="1*"/>
      <tbody>
      <row>
      <entry><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mi>p</mi></math></entry>
      <entry xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mi>q</mi></math></entry>
      <entry xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mo>~</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow></math></entry>
