      <example id="exam-00003">
      <title>Applying the Chain Rule for Conditional Arguments to Determine a Valid and Sound Conclusion</title>
      <exercise id="exer-00005">
      <problem id="prob-00005">
      <para id="para-00039">Each pair of statements represent true premises in a logical argument. Based on these premises, apply the chain rule for conditional arguments to determine a valid and sound conclusion.</para>
      <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha" id="list-00006">
      <item>If Jessica goes to work, then Jessica will get paid. If Jessica gets paid, then Jessica will pay her bills.</item>
      <item>If robins can fly, then some birds can fly. If some birds can fly, then John will watch birds fly.</item>
      <item>If Irma is a teacher, then Irma has a college degree. If Irma has a college degree, then Irma graduated from college.</item>
      </list>
      </problem>
      <solution id="sol-00003">
      <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="lower-alpha" id="list-00007">
      <item>The premises are: <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>q</mi><mo>:</mo></mrow></math> If Jessica goes to work, then Jessica will get paid. and <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>q</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>:</mo></mrow></math> If Jessica gets paid, then Jessica will pay her bills. This argument has the form of the chain rule for conditional arguments, so, the valid conclusion will have the form, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>.</mo></mrow></math> Because, all the premises are true, the valid and sound conclusion of this argument is: If Jessica goes to work, then Jessica will pay her bills.</item>
      <item xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">The premises are: <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>q</mi><mo>:</mo></mrow></math> If robins can fly, then some birds can fly and <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>q</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>:</mo></mrow></math> If some birds can fly, then John will watch them fly. This argument has the form of the chain rule for conditional arguments, so, the valid conclusion will have the form, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>.</mo></mrow></math> Because, all the premises are true, the valid and sound conclusion of this argument is: If robins can fly, then John will watch birds fly.</item>
      <item xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">The premises are: If Irma is a teacher, then Irma has a college degree and <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>q</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>:</mo></mrow></math> If Irma has a college degree, then Irma graduated from college.  This argument has the form of the chain rule for conditional arguments, so, the valid conclusion will have the form, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>.</mo></mrow></math> Because, all the premises are true, the valid and sound conclusion of this argument is: If Irma is a teacher, then Irma graduated from college.</item>
      </list>
      </solution>
      </exercise>
      </example>
