      <section class="projects" id="sect-00007">
      <title>Projects</title>
      <list list-type="labeled-item" id="list-00008">
      <item><label>1)</label><para id="para-00055">Logic Gates</para>
      <para id="para-00056">Logic gates are the basis for all digital circuits.</para>
      <list list-type="labeled-item" id="list-00009">
      <item><label>a)</label><para id="para-00057">Research and document the following terms: logic gate, OR gate, AND gate, and NOT gate.</para>
      <para id="para-00058">Answer: Will define terms as described.</para>
      </item>
      <item><label>b)</label><para id="para-00059">Construct a diagram of a NAND gate, NOR gate, and a XOR gate by using at least two of the following gates: AND, OR, and NOT.</para>
      <para id="para-00060">Answer: Answers will vary.</para>
      </item>
      <item><label>c)</label><para id="para-00061">Digital Electronics uses a 1 for true or on, and a 0 for false or off. Create a truth table, documenting all possible cases using 0’s and 1’s for the NAND gate, NOR gate and XOR gate.</para>
      <para id="para-00062">Answer: Must demonstrate understanding of the truth tables for the NAND, NOR and XOR gates.</para>
      </item>
      <item><label>d)</label><para id="para-00063">Use a truth table to explain how XOR is related to the biconditional statement.</para>
      <para id="para-00064">Answer: The biconditional statement is equivalent to the negation of XOR.</para>
      </item>
      </list>
      </item>
      <item><label>2)</label><para id="para-00065">Logical Fallacies</para>
      <para id="para-00066">Fallacies are false or deceptive logical arguments.</para>
      <list list-type="labeled-item" id="list-00010">
      <item><label>a)</label><para id="para-00067">Research and document the structure of five of the following named fallacies: hasty generalization, limited choice, false cause, appeal to popularity, appeal to emotion, appeal to authority, personal attack, gamblers’ ruin, slippery slope, and circular reasoning.</para>
      <para id="para-00068">Answer: Will vary based on fallacies chosen.</para>
      </item>
      <item><label>b)</label><para id="para-00069">Create a presentation highlighting one of the five fallacies researched in part a).  The presentation must include an introductory slide with the title of the fallacy and the form or structure of the argument. The second slide must include an example of this fallacy as used in a commercial, a political cartoon or a current event or new article. The third slide must include an explanation of why the example on slide to is a representative example of the fallacy.  The last slide must include citations for any materials used. No textbooks should be used as reference.</para>
      <para id="para-00070">Answer: Will vary based on fallacies chosen and resources used.</para>
      </item>
      </list>
      </item>
      <item><label>3)</label><para id="para-00071">Careers in Logic</para>
      <para id="para-00072">Lawyers, Mathematicians, and Computer Programmers are of few of the careers that require knowledge of logic. What career are you interested in?</para>
      <para id="para-00073">Research how knowledge of logic applies to your given field of study, then write a cover letter to apply for a position in your field that includes how your knowledge of logic qualifies you for the position you are applying for. If you don't think logic is important for your given career choice, find a position that does and complete the project by pretending you are writing a cover letter for that job.</para>
      </item>
      </list>
